L5. Altekar says pa of saṁpadayā is damaged. In my scan, the whole of padayā is indistinct, but the first character doesn't look like pa. This bit is lost from the parallel inscription. I find saṁpadayā doubtful, the noun saṁpadā would be non-standard for sampad. Altekar translates "prosperity produced by the richness (i.e. excellence) of his karman (i, bravery, ii, religious merit), which is dodgy. 
--><!-- 
L7. There is a concave semicircle above the anusvāra of dhārāṁ. (Altekar) This feature is discussed in #Altekar_1947:254. 
--><!-- 
L8. I follow Altekar's bbrā, but the character is not visible at all in my scanned facsimile, and this inscription tends not to double consonants (apparently never before r and usually not after r, though rddhā in l7 is correct. 
--><!-- 
L14. There is a concave semicircle above the anusvāra of both instances of vaṁśe. (Altekar) 
--><!-- 
L15. I follow Venkataramayya's reading of the names. My scan is useless. Altekar reads jayanartana; followed by a reconstructed prabhāgravarddhana (admitting that prabhāgra is "completely damaged"); in 15-16 he reads sogineta em. soginetuḥ (?śrī)somasyā° 
--><!-- 
L16. I retain Altekar's supplied daṇḍa after dakṣiṇā, but it seems unnecessary in light of the very plausible restoration of the end. 
--></p>
